@channel Hi all - Weve made the tough decision to end new enrollment into the iOS program. iOS was one of our early new programs, and while students whove completed the program have had great outcomes, weve not been able to sustain enrollment in the program. We faced a decision of doubling down to ensure enrollment in the iOS program, or directing that energy toward our Web and DS programs. We chose the latter.
Our commitment and support to our current iOS students is unwavering. We have detailed plans in place to support both our FT and PT iOS students through the remainder of their time at Lambda School. Instructors will continue to follow through the core curriculum, the students will continue into Computer Science, Labs, and our guided job search, and will be supported long-term as alumni, like all Lambda graduates.
We want to recognize @Ben, @Paul Solt, @Spencer Curtis, and all of our Part-Time instructors for everything theyve done to build the program, and for all they continue to do for and with our students. Thank you.

Hi everybody! As you know, flex is an important tool in Lambdas program to reinforce mastery-based learning. Providing students an opportunity to repeat curriculum, when necessary, helps everyone build a solid foundation before they progress. And were working hard to improve this process and experience for you.On that note, I wanted to share an update to the flex policy and some quick reminders (and if you prefer video to reading, please check out the video below): New: We will no longer do mid-unit flex. You will continue with the curriculum for sprints 1-3 and only have the option to flex at the end of a unit.
  • If you need to flex, you will use the Build Sprint to study the areas that you need to improve and then start at day 1, sprint 1 of the next section.
  • Even if you will be flexing at the end of the unit, you still need to attend class, 1:1s, standup, and submit daily modules and Sprint Challenges. The goal is to keep trying!
Reminder: Sprint Challenges are timed tests. All Sprint Challenges must be turned in by the deadline: 11am Friday for FT and by end of class on 5th day Week B for PT.
  • Even if you are not finished you need to submit the challenge by the deadline.
  • Failure to submit on time will result in an automatic score of 1 and you will not be able to reattempt for a passing score.
  • Resubmissions are due: 5pm Friday for FT and start of class Tuesday week A for PT.
Reminder: Final resubmissions for sprints 1-3 are due by the resubmission deadline of sprint 3: 5pm Friday for FT and start of class Tuesday week A for PT.Thanks for reading and please reach out if you have any questions via /frontdesk. And heres Jessica Pense, our Director of Student Success, to walk you through these updates:

Hi Everyone,For those of you who dont know, this Friday is Juneteenth. As America continues to confront and address the unacceptable levels of institutional and systemic cultural racism that Black Americans face daily, we thought it was especially important to take a moment to recognize and stand with our Black students and staff in the celebration of Juneteenth and the abolishment of the institution of slavery in America.Juneteenth (a combination of June and nineteen) is the oldest celebration of the end of slavery in America. Juneteenth celebrations date back to 1865. On June 19, 1865, Major General Gordon Granger, and a group of Union soldiers landed in Galveston, Texas, declaring the end of Civil war and slavery. Although President Lincoln signed the Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, this had little impact on Texas since there were no Union forces to carry out these orders. More than two years later, General Robert E. Lee surrendered, allowing the Union soldiers to overpower the resistance and enforce the law.Texas was the first state to make Juneteenth a holiday in 1980. Today, 47 states and Washington D.C. recognize the day. It is usually celebrated with festivals, parades, storytelling, picnics, and barbeques. For more on Juneteenth, you can check out this page. Because we are closing the whole week of June 29th as a school and to minimize disruption to students (youll notice that Lambda does not right now observe most federal holidays, opting instead to give students and staff rest through longer breaks throughout the year), we are not going to close the school for Juneteenth this year.Lets continue to listen, learn and act as we all go forward together to create a better world for everyone. We know there are so many great resources available on the struggles of Black Americans, how to support the Black community and how to be an ally. Heres one created by Lambda team members we wanted to share (and invite you to contribute, if youd like).Thank you for all of your hard work and all you bring to our Lambda community.

Austen Allred  5:31 PM
Hi all,This week, we received some important information from the California Bureau of Private and Postsecondary Education (BPPE) -- the body that regulates higher education and tuition in California -- that we wanted to share with all of you, even though it only pertains to students based in California. The short summary of this post is that for all of you -- all students -- nothing changes, even if youre based in California. But here is a longer explanation:As a quick background: we submitted our application to the BPPE over a year ago, and since then have been working closely with them. We have a team dedicated to compliance, and working with the BPPE has been one of their top priorities. This process has included 6+ months of active conversations with regulators, 500 pages of filings and forms, trips to Sacramento, and hundreds of thousands of dollars spent.On Monday, we received notice that the BPPE sent back an initial denial of our application based on our model for helping students finance their education. The good news is that this initial decision has nothing to do with the quality of our programs, our educational model, or anything related to the School itself. The decision was entirely related to the way we help students pay for their education using Income Share Agreements (ISAs). In contrast with traditional educational institutions, Lambda invests in the success of our students. When students succeed when you succeed we succeed. If you fail, we fail. That is the fundamental premise of the ISA. This accountability distinguishes Lambda from traditional forms of education and training, like college or most vocational training programs.As you know, the vast majority of our students choose the Lambda School ISA and so pay us nothing up front. Unlike traditional student loans, Income Share Agreements (ISAs) are fundamentally designed to protect students and alumni. While the monthly payment for typical student loans generally remains fixed regardless of employment status or income, Lambda Schools ISAs automatically adjust based on your current salary as reported to our servicer -- that protection is already built in. Moreover, if your annual income drops below $50,000, your ISA payments will be suspended until youre back above that mark.The same dynamics that make ISAs so appealing to all of our students are the ones that make ISAs unattractive for regulators: ISA payments vary based on your income, and Lambda does not obligate students to repay a fixed amount for our courses and placement services. Fundamentally, we bet that we can train you and help you find a job making more than $50,000 per year -- and what you repay us depends on those dynamics so it can be anywhere between $0 and $30,000. ISAs don't fit neatly in the existing regulatory box designed for traditional education or traditional student loans. This issue is much bigger than just Lambda. There are multiple institutions across the country and currently in California that use ISAs to help students finance their education. We founded Lambda on the belief that the whole educational model will work better if our incentives are aligned with yours -- ISAs are critical to that belief. We know from experience how important ISAs are to all of you. We polled the Lambda student body a few months ago asking if you would have attended Lambda without the option of an ISA, and 93% of you said no. You confirmed what we already know -- that ISAs expand access to high quality education and thus to economic opportunity.  I believe the economic situation in the United States and globally makes expanding access and our work even more urgent.So what happens now? For you, nothing changes, even if you are a student based in California. This is just the latest step in a long process with BPPE, and while it was disappointing it was not unexpected. We will continue to work with them as well as other regulators in California to explain our position, demonstrate how ISAs expand educational access and make adjustments if necessary.For us, were appealing the decision. It took over a year for the BPPE to review our application, so we expect this process to take a while. We will continue to keep you posted as we get updates.We wanted to be sure you heard about this from us first. I encourage you to stay focused on your goals -- on learning to code and on finding a job. Our top priority is for you to succeed.AustenFAQsWhat does this mean for current non-CA students and their ISAs?
This ruling only relates to California students. All our non-California students are not affected by this.What does this mean for current CA students and their ISAs? Theres no change for students as we continue to work with BPPE on this decision. Your ISA is a contract between you and Lambda School, where we agree on how youll pay for the value you receive from Lambda in terms of classes and other ways that Lambda School prepares you for a well-paying job.

Is there any issue with Lambda School education? No. There has never been any question about the quality of education at Lambda School. This initial denial was based only on how ISAs work.

Is BPPE looking to shut down Lambda School? We do not anticipate this as a possibility for our California students based both on past precedent and on our ongoing conversations with BPPE. We have done everything required and will continue our discussions with the BPPE on the ISA issue.

Heather Spain  6:01 PM
@channel
Hi, all! I hope everyone had a great weekend. We just published our Diversity Report for 2020 and wanted to share it with all of you. The report includes data and demographics on both students and staff. A huge thank you to all who took the survey earlier this summer. The survey data in this report creates an important baseline understanding that well use to inform how well expand our support for diversity, equity and inclusion at Lambda School. We plan to release staff and student diversity reports annually, though we may not always release them at the same time going forward. Throughout the year, well keep you updated on how were working to make sure Lambda School is a supportive, welcoming and inclusive community where anyone can feel like they belong, regardless of circumstance or background.You can read the full report here. Also, please check out the FAQ below.Thanks again for your help with this important work.  FAQWhy is this the first time Lambda School is releasing this data?
We are a young company, but we recognize the importance of accountability and the value of performance metrics. As part of our broader initiative to be more accountable and transparent, this is our first Diversity Report, which we will release annually. We know we have a lot to learn, but we begin the process certain that the best way to make progress is to put stakes in the ground measuring our performance across several dimensions. How will Lambda School use these results? 
Well publish them annually and use them as a guide and source of accountability for the necessary work we need to continue to do to improve diversity and inclusion. Were students required to disclose personal information?
No. Students were not required to respond to the survey at all and were not required to answer every question (in other words, students could choose to opt out of questions if they preferred).Will you survey new students or students in the future?
Yes! This survey will become part of the admissions process.Can you identify students by their individual responses to questions? Is the survey confidential?
The survey is fully confidential. No single student will ever be identified by their responses. All the data was aggregated and findings reported based on the data pool. For more, please see Lambda School's Privacy Policy.Why did you group certain demographic categories together? 
We used guidelines from the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity (EEOC) and National Science Foundation (NSF) to guide these categories. Like these organizations do, we allowed for a wide range of self-selected answers so all respondents felt properly represented. That led to a very long tail of various responses, so in reporting these in a public, visual medium we had to group some categories together for organization purposes and readability. You can read more in the methodology section of the report.

Austen Allred  2:03 PM
@channelHi all I wanted to personally share some very good news with you all today -- Lambda School has been officially approved for operation by the Bureau for Private Postsecondary Education (BPPE) in California. This approval is a massive milestone and represents a major endorsement of the career-focused educational model weve all built together. In order to work within the states existing regulatory framework and secure this approval, we made the decision to change some of our financings options for new, incoming students in California. Weve introduced a new option called a Retail Installment Contract (RIC). Unfortunately, we will not be able to offer ISAs to new students in CA for the foreseeable future. Were letting you know because we want to keep this community up-to-date. This will not impact current CA students with an ISA in any way. You can learn more about the RIC option for new students in our FAQ here.

As weve said before, regulatory approval is crucial for setting a precedent for better student protection, broader adoption, and greater access to education. We still believe ISAs are one of the most student-friendly, lowest-risk alternative to traditional student debt, and we plan to continue to advocate for it in California and the rest of the U.S., but are thrilled that we can still offer a consumer-friendly option to incoming California students as we work toward that goal.
You can read more about the approval here.

@here Hey everyone, this has been a big and busy week. Ive been in conversations with many of you and your cohorts, and I know there are a lot of questions, concerns, and feedback, and I wanted to share a few updates to the whole school.The headline: were going to run a schoolwide survey tomorrow on the new changes this week, and we are using that plus your feedback from Front Desk and Canvas submissions to prioritize improvements to the new program.First, thank you to all of you who have provided feedback in constructive ways on the program changes that we rolled out this week. I mentioned in the Assembly that students are at their best when they own their learning, and those of you that are opinionated and engaged are exemplifying that. Weve heard the most feedback about Lambda Leadership, specifically around the changes with peer mentoring, but weve also gotten good feedback on the new shortened school, Canvas, and other changes around assessment and the time commitments from the new changes.There are some core philosophical and program goals that were working towards with these changes. We care deeply about learning, and these changes are all designed with the end goal that more students are more successful at landing great jobs after graduating. With that said, we know with any change of this magnitude, there are implementation details that we have to learn from and iterate on. One of my favorite things about being at Lambda instead of a traditional school is that we can move quickly. While its hard to move as quickly as we could when we were 10-20 people, we can iterate and improve on a week over week and month over month basis. Weve launched new changes this week, were taking in your feedback, and well learn and iterate. The entire team and I are committed to that.Were actively watching three areas for that feedback:
  1. Your module and sprint submissions in Canvas. Instructors and our Student Success teams are reviewing responses and adjusting their day-to-day based on how youre doing. Were also reviewing and collating feedback on the program changes.
  2. Your submissions through Front Desk. (We know theres a backlog here, the entire team is working as hard as they can to get caught up!) Were tagging every inbound request so we have a complete picture of where we need to focus.
  3. An early-impressions survey on the changes that well be rolling out tomorrow that covers the Lambda Leadership specifically. Well use the survey to understand what is going well, what is not going well, and where we focus first.
Well run the survey from tomorrow through Monday morning, so please take the time to help us know where to focus our efforts next week. On top of those three areas, weve been in a number of one-on-one and cohort conversations with many of you as well. Thank you for making the time for those.Second, there are a few early themes from the feedback that I wanted to let you know were talking about as a team. Based on the survey results and comprehensive review of the inbound feedback, well prioritize what changes will come first. Here are the themes were seeing:
  • A better understanding of why were making these changes.
  • Concerns around the amount of added time Lambda Leadership takes from each module, especially in Part Time.
  • Questions around the new assessment model, and making sure youre getting the support and accountability you need.
  • Questions around why some changes were rolled out to the whole school vs opt-in or for new cohorts only.
These arent the only questions, but are the strongest early themes this week. As you submit to Front Desk or on the survey tomorrow, please let us know if theres more.Thank you again for all youre doing, for giving these changes a shot, for your feedback, and in-advance for your help on the survey. Watch for the survey link tomorrow, and as we close out the week, I hope you all stay safe and have a great weekend.

@here 
Happy Thursday, Lambda School!TL;DR: 
Election season is upon us for those of us in the U.S. With hotly-debated issues taking center stage, the presidential election can be a tense time. Theres a lot going on in our country and the world, and the stakes feel particularly high for many people. And though were first and foremost a school and our platforms are intended primarily for your Lambda education and job search, we wanted to share guidelines and resources for how to engage in political conversations, if you choose. Reminder that Lambda will be closed on Tuesday, Nov. 3rd for election day. Well follow-up mid-next week with details about how this affects school schedules and any project due dates.At Lambda, we work hard to build a community thats welcoming and inclusive, regardless of how an individual identifies, including political affiliation. This is a space for all of our students to learn, grow, and land an amazing job. That said, below are our expectations and guidelines for those who choose to engage in conversations regarding the election and political issues (and extend to any conversation, actually). These expectations and guidelines arent new or temporary and stem from our overall Code of Conduct. They serve as a reminder of the community and culture we want to build for everyone at Lambda. Guidelines for engaging in critical discussions:
  • Conversations regarding politics, presidential and vice presidential debates, legislation, supreme court nominees, etc. are to be kept in the #politics channel. 
  • Think carefully prior to posting (on Slack, social media, etc.). What message are you trying to send? Regardless of intent, what impact might your post have on others? When in doubt or if youre unable to engage in a professional or respectful conversation, avoid posting or responding. 
  • The color of someones skin, country of origin, womens healthcare and reproductive rights, sexual and gender orientation, socio-economic status, etc. have become political issues in our country. If youre engaging in conversations around these topics, please keep in mind that none of us can understand the lived experiences of others. 
  • If someone tells you your behavior and or/comments were harmful to them, please listen and hear them. This can be *hard* -- we know our instincts are often to slide into defensive mode and react, but staying open and trying to understand what someone is saying in these situations is so important.
  • Assume best intent. Give others the benefit of the doubt as you try to clarify the meaning of what they said and their intent.
Lambda is a professional environment and we expect professional behavior. This is a space where we want you to engage with your fellow students, build community, and have enriching conversations. We wont, however, tolerate bullying, harassment, discrimination, or harmful behavior directed at any group or individual. We want to respect students and instructors time and wont tolerate disruption of time thats intended for coursework. This includes, but is not limited to: Guided Projects, office hours, peer mentor/mentee meetings, and Track Team meetings. We reserve the right to delete any post, message, or thread that violates these expectations or is viewed as harmful to our community. Additionally, we reserve the right to deactivate the Slack access of any student who is unwilling to stop or change behavior that is non compliant. There are many resources available on navigating difficult conversations. Here are a few that may be helpful: 
2:02
  • Celeste Headlee: How to Talk About Politics Constructively
  • Megan Phelps-Roper: 4 Tips for Talking to People you Disagree With
  • Living Room Conversations' Talking Politics resources
Finally, please take care of yourself. Election season and all thats going on in the world right now can take its toll on our mental health. Here are some tips from Modern Health therapist Roy Woods on coping with stress before and after election day. To learn more about all of the free resources you can access through Modern Health, please see this page on My Lambda.  (edited)

@here
We know some of you have been affected by Hurricane Zeta, which has hit the Southeast. We hope everyone is safe. If youve lost power/internet connection, once you are safe and sound, you can let /frontdesk know. Please take care. With Halloween only a few days away -- and under a full moon this year -- were in the midst of spooky season, full of monsters, mummies and ghosts. Whether youre a huge Halloween fan or if its not your thing (and recognizing that any Halloween celebrating will look pretty different this year amidst the global pandemic), theres another monster that lurks nearby that most of us are familiar with. Its the monster that tells us were not good enough, we shouldnt be here, we cant cut it, etc. Its otherwise known as imposter syndrome.If youve experienced or are struggling with imposter syndrome, you are not alone. I repeat: YOU ARE NOT ALONE! While its safe to say the majority of us have experienced imposter syndrome at one time or another () we may be more vulnerable to it when were doing something new, out of our comfort zone, challenging and fast-paced -- sound familiar? And while it may be impossible to prevent imposter syndrome, the good news is there are tons of resources and tips for managing it. Weve surfaced some of our favorite nuggets  of wisdom from Lambda Career Coaches, students and Alumni:Imposter syndrome. Its real and I felt it the entire program (and still do). I always wanted to be able to post in the hired channel and never thought I would get here. There are people who are literally twice to ten times more technically proficient than me right here at Lambda School but you cant compare yourself to anyone else. Stay in your lane and run the race. All you can do is get better every day according to what you knew yesterday. - @Ryan Cooper, WEB26 alumnus, (from #hired channel, re-shared with permission)You have joined a field where you will always be learning so embrace the fact that you will never know everything and be proud of what you do know. - @Rachel Cohen, Career CoachReach out to and listen to stories from people who have been in your shoes and made it to where you want to go. Ask them about their own experiences with imposter syndrome. Similarly, find people you trust to be vulnerable with and express your fears with, especially those in the same boat as you.

Fact check your own thoughts! When you have a negative thought about yourself, is there any evidence to actually support it?
